        <section id="lesson-2" class="content-section fade-in-up">
          <h2>Lesson 2: Pheromones</h2>

          <p>
            In Week 3 you learned about <strong>chemotaxis</strong> — directional movement towards
            or away from a chemical stimulus. Pheromones are one of the most important chemical
            signals in nature, and the responses they trigger are textbook examples of chemotaxis
            in action.
          </p>


          <!-- ── What Are Pheromones? ── -->
          <h3>What Are Pheromones?</h3>

          <p>
            <strong>Pheromones</strong> are chemical substances secreted by an organism into the
            external environment that trigger a specific behavioural or physiological response in
            another member of the <strong>same species</strong>. The term was coined in 1959 by
            Karlson and Lüscher, from the Greek <em>pherein</em> (to carry) and <em>hormon</em>
            (to excite).
          </p>

          <div class="key-concept">
            <h4>Pheromones vs Hormones</h4>
            <div class="table-wrapper">
              <table class="stimuli-table">
                <thead>
                  <tr>
                    <th>Feature</th>
                    <th>Pheromone</th>
                    <th>Hormone</th>
                  </tr>
                </thead>
                <tbody>
                  <tr>
                    <td><strong>Target</strong></td>
                    <td>Other individuals of the same species</td>
                    <td>The organism's own cells / tissues</td>
                  </tr>
                  <tr>
                    <td><strong>Transmission</strong></td>
                    <td>Released into the external environment (air, water, surface)</td>
                    <td>Transported internally via blood / haemolymph</td>
                  </tr>
                  <tr>
                    <td><strong>Concentration</strong></td>
                    <td>Detected at extraordinarily low levels (parts per trillion)</td>
                    <td>Relatively higher concentrations in blood</td>
                  </tr>
                  <tr>
                    <td><strong>Produced by</strong></td>
                    <td>Exocrine glands (secreted externally)</td>
                    <td>Endocrine glands (secreted internally)</td>
                  </tr>
                </tbody>
              </table>
            </div>
          </div>


          <!-- ── Releaser vs Primer ── -->
          <h3>Releaser vs Primer Pheromones</h3>

          <p>
            Not all pheromones work the same way. The two major categories tell us about
            <em>how fast</em> the response occurs and <em>what system</em> is affected.
          </p>

          <div class="key-concept">
            <div class="concept-pair">
              <div class="concept-card concept-card--releaser">
                <h5>Releaser Pheromones</h5>
                <p>
                  Trigger an <strong>immediate, rapid behavioural response</strong> in the receiver.
                  The response is fast and stereotypic — it acts on the <strong>nervous system</strong>.
                </p>
                <div class="concept-example">
                  <span class="example-label">Examples</span>
                  Alarm pheromones causing flight or defence; sex pheromones triggering courtship;
                  trail pheromones guiding foraging ants.
                </div>
              </div>

              <div class="concept-card concept-card--primer">
                <h5>Primer Pheromones</h5>
                <p>
                  Trigger a <strong>slow, long-term physiological change</strong> in the receiver
                  over days or weeks. They act on the <strong>endocrine system</strong>, altering
                  hormone levels.
                </p>
                <div class="concept-example">
                  <span class="example-label">Examples</span>
                  Honeybee queen substance suppressing worker ovary development; the Bruce Effect
                  in mice causing pregnancy termination.
                </div>
              </div>
            </div>
          </div>

          <div class="exam-tip">
            <h4>Exam Tip</h4>
            <p>
              A single pheromone can be <strong>both</strong> a releaser and a primer. Honeybee
              queen mandibular pheromone (QMP) acts as a releaser (immediately attracts workers
              to groom the queen) <strong>and</strong> a primer (suppresses worker ovary
              development over weeks). Examiners love this example.
            </p>
          </div>


          <!-- ── Types of Pheromones ── -->
          <h3>Types of Pheromones</h3>

          <div class="pheromone-types-grid">

            <div class="pheromone-type-card">
              <div class="pheromone-type-card__icon" aria-hidden="true">
                <svg width="40" height="40" viewBox="0 0 40 40" fill="none">
                  <circle cx="14" cy="20" r="6" stroke="var(--fluoro-pink)" stroke-width="1.5"/>
