              <h4>Aggregation Pheromones</h4>
              <p>
                Attract <strong>both sexes</strong> to a location (unlike sex pheromones). Often used
                to overwhelm a host's defences through mass attack — bark beetles use these to
                coordinate attacks on trees.
              </p>
              <span class="pheromone-type-badge pheromone-type-badge--releaser">Releaser</span>
            </div>

            <div class="pheromone-type-card">
              <div class="pheromone-type-card__icon" aria-hidden="true">
                <svg width="40" height="40" viewBox="0 0 40 40" fill="none">
                  <rect x="8" y="12" width="24" height="16" rx="3" stroke="var(--purple-light)" stroke-width="1.5" fill="none"/>
                  <path d="M8 20h24" stroke="var(--purple-light)" stroke-width="1" stroke-dasharray="3 2"/>
                  <circle cx="20" cy="20" r="2" fill="var(--purple-light)"/>
                </svg>
              </div>
              <h4>Territorial Marking</h4>
              <p>
                Deposited to define and defend territory boundaries. Common in mammals via urine,
                faeces, or specialised glands. NZ kiwi may use faecal scent-marking to define
                territories.
              </p>
              <span class="pheromone-type-badge pheromone-type-badge--both">Both</span>
            </div>

            <div class="pheromone-type-card">
              <div class="pheromone-type-card__icon" aria-hidden="true">
