          <!-- ── How Pheromones Are Detected ── -->
          <h3>How Pheromones Are Detected</h3>

          <p>
            The detection mechanism differs between invertebrates and vertebrates — and this
            distinction matters for exam answers.
          </p>

          <div class="key-concept">
            <div class="concept-pair">
              <div class="concept-card concept-card--detection-insect">
                <h5>Insects: Antennal Chemoreceptors</h5>
                <p>
                  Insect antennae contain thousands of <strong>sensilla</strong> — tiny hair-like
                  structures housing olfactory receptor neurons. Pheromone molecules enter through
                  pores and bind to <strong>odorant-binding proteins</strong>, which ferry them to
                  receptor proteins on sensory neurons.
                </p>
                <p>
                  Each specialist neuron is "tuned" to one specific pheromone component. Male moths
                  often have <strong>feathery (plumose) antennae</strong> with vastly more sensilla
                  than females, maximising surface area for pheromone detection.
                </p>
              </div>

              <div class="concept-card concept-card--detection-vertebrate">
                <h5>Vertebrates: Vomeronasal Organ (VNO)</h5>
                <p>
                  Also called <strong>Jacobson's organ</strong> — a specialised chemosensory structure
                  separate from the main olfactory epithelium. Found in many reptiles, amphibians,
                  and mammals.
                </p>
                <p>
                  Signals travel to the <strong>accessory olfactory bulb → amygdala → hypothalamus</strong>,
                  triggering behavioural or endocrine responses. The <strong>flehmen response</strong>
                  (lip curl) in mammals helps draw pheromone molecules into the VNO.
                </p>
              </div>
            </div>
          </div>

