          <!-- ── Adaptive Advantages ── -->
          <h3>Adaptive Advantages of Pheromone Communication</h3>

          <ul class="feature-list feature-list--advantages">
            <li><strong>Works in darkness</strong> — effective for nocturnal species (most NZ native moths, wētā)</li>
            <li><strong>Works over vast distances</strong> — sex pheromones detected kilometres downwind</li>
            <li><strong>Species-specific</strong> — precise chemical ratios prevent wasted reproductive effort</li>
            <li><strong>Low energy cost</strong> — only nanograms needed to produce a signal</li>
            <li><strong>Self-dissipating</strong> — alarm and trail pheromones fade when no longer relevant</li>
            <li><strong>Encodes quality information</strong> — ants deposit more trail pheromone for better food</li>
            <li><strong>Coordinates colony behaviour</strong> — enables eusocial organisation without centralised control</li>
          </ul>

          <div class="summary-box">
            <h4>Connection to Chemotaxis</h4>
            <p>
              Pheromone-guided movement is a <strong>taxis</strong> (directional), not a kinesis
              (non-directional). A male moth flying upwind along a pheromone plume demonstrates
              <strong>positive chemotaxis</strong> combined with <strong>anemotaxis</strong>
              (orientation to wind direction). An ant following a trail to food is performing
              positive chemotaxis along an increasing concentration gradient.
            </p>
          </div>
