              <div class="example-card__body">
                <p>
                  In 1959, Adolf Butenandt's team isolated the first pheromone by processing the
                  abdominal tips of over <strong>500,000 female silkworm moths</strong> over 20 years.
                  The compound, named <strong>bombykol</strong>, is a 16-carbon alcohol
                  ((10E,12Z)-hexadeca-10,12-dien-1-ol).
                </p>
                <p class="example-card__detail">
                  A single female carries only ~0.01 micrograms, yet males can detect it at
                  concentrations of <strong>10<sup>−12</sup> micrograms per mL</strong> from
                  several kilometres downwind. Other stereoisomers of the molecule were
                  100–1,000,000× less active — demonstrating the critical importance of
                  molecular geometry in pheromone specificity.
