                <p>
                  Workers deposit trail pheromone <strong>only on the return journey</strong> after
                  finding food — not on the outward search. More rewarding food = more pheromone
                  deposited. The result: a <strong>positive feedback loop</strong> where more ants
                  on a trail = more pheromone = more ants recruited.
                </p>
                <p class="example-card__detail">
                  This is a textbook example of <strong>emergent behaviour</strong> — complex
                  colony-level optimisation from simple individual rules, without any centralised
                  control. When food is exhausted, ants stop reinforcing the trail and it
                  evaporates — a self-correcting system.
                </p>
              </div>
            </div>

            <!-- Elephant -->
            <div class="example-card example-card--global">
              <div class="example-card__header">
                <h4>Asian Elephant — Context-Dependent Response</h4>
                <span class="example-card__latin">Elephas maximus</span>
                <span class="response-badge response-badge--pheromone">Frontalin (musth)</span>
              </div>
              <div class="example-card__body">
                <p>
                  Males in musth (annual testosterone surge — up to 140× normal) secrete
                  <strong>frontalin</strong> from their temporal glands. The same pheromone
                  <strong>attracts</strong> receptive females but <strong>repels</strong> subadult males.
                </p>
                <p class="example-card__detail">
                  This elegantly demonstrates that the response to a pheromone depends on the
                  <strong>physiological state of the receiver</strong>, not just the chemical signal.
                  Females approaching ovulation produce (Z)-7-dodecenyl acetate, detected by males
                  via the vomeronasal organ.
                </p>
              </div>
            </div>

            <!-- Bruce Effect -->
            <div class="example-card example-card--global">
              <div class="example-card__header">
                <h4>The Bruce Effect — Primer Pheromone in Mice</h4>
                <span class="example-card__latin">Mus musculus</span>
                <span class="response-badge response-badge--pheromone">Primer (pregnancy block)</span>
              </div>
              <div class="example-card__body">
                <p>
                  If a recently mated female mouse is exposed to pheromones from an
                  <strong>unfamiliar male</strong> (not the father), she may spontaneously
                  abort the pregnancy. The strange male's urinary pheromones are detected via the VNO
                  and trigger a neuroendocrine cascade that blocks prolactin release.
                </p>
                <p class="example-card__detail">
                  <strong>Adaptive advantage:</strong> prevents the female investing in offspring
                  that the new dominant male would likely kill (infanticide avoidance). Discovered
                  by Hilda Bruce in 1959 — the same year as bombykol.
                </p>
              </div>
            </div>

          </div>
        </section>


