        <section id="lesson-3" class="content-section fade-in-up" data-release="2026-02-19">
          <h2>Lessons 3–4: Navigation</h2>

          <p>
            Taxes and kineses explain how organisms orient to <strong>local stimuli</strong> — a
            light source, a chemical gradient, a moisture difference. But many animals travel
            <strong>hundreds or thousands of kilometres</strong> between breeding and feeding
            grounds, crossing featureless ocean or open sky. How do they know where to go?
          </p>

          <p>
            Navigation is the ability to <strong>determine and maintain a course toward a
            specific destination</strong>. It goes beyond simple orientation — the animal must
            have some form of "map" (knowing where it is relative to its goal) and a "compass"
            (knowing which direction to travel).
          </p>


          <!-- ── Piloting: Landmarks & Familiar Routes ── -->
          <h3>Piloting: Landmarks &amp; Familiar Routes</h3>

          <p>
            The simplest form of navigation. Animals follow a series of <strong>learned visual
            landmarks</strong> — coastlines, rivers, mountain ranges, even roads. This requires
            <strong>prior experience</strong> of the route.
          </p>

          <div class="key-concept">
            <h4>How Piloting Works</h4>
            <p>
              The animal recognises a sequence of familiar features and uses each one to orient
              toward the next. Think of it like following a series of road signs — you don't need
              to know your GPS coordinates, you just need to recognise the next turn.
            </p>
            <div class="concept-example">
              <span class="example-label">Example</span>
              <p>
                <strong>Homing pigeons</strong> released near home use familiar landmarks for the
                final approach, even if they used other cues (sun compass, magnetic field) for the
                long-distance phase. Young pigeons that haven't learned the local landmarks take
                longer to find the loft than experienced birds.
              </p>
            </div>
          </div>

          <div class="exam-tip">
            <h4>Exam Tip</h4>
            <p>
              Piloting is limited — it only works in <strong>familiar territory</strong> and fails
              over featureless ocean or at night. This is why long-distance migrants need additional
              compass mechanisms. A strong answer explains <em>why</em> piloting alone is insufficient.
            </p>
          </div>


          <!-- ── Sun Compass ── -->
          <h3>Sun Compass Navigation</h3>

          <p>
            Many animals use the <strong>position of the sun</strong> relative to the horizon as a
            directional reference. Because the sun moves across the sky (~15° per hour), the animal
            must compensate for this movement using an <strong>internal circadian clock</strong> —
            this is called <strong>time-compensated sun compass navigation</strong>.
          </p>

          <div class="key-concept">
            <h4>Time-Compensated Sun Compass</h4>
            <div class="concept-pair">
              <div class="concept-card concept-card--sun">
                <h5>The Compass</h5>
                <p>
                  The sun's position provides directional information. In the Southern Hemisphere,
                  the sun is due north at solar noon. An animal "knows" that if the sun is to its
                  left in the morning, it is heading roughly south.
                </p>
              </div>
              <div class="concept-card concept-card--clock">
                <h5>The Clock</h5>
                <p>
                  The animal's internal circadian clock tracks the time of day, allowing it to
                  compensate for the sun's apparent movement. Without this clock, a bee trained to
                  find food to the east in the morning would search to the south at midday.
                </p>
              </div>
            </div>
          </div>

          <!-- Sun compass diagram -->
          <div class="nav-diagram">
            <h4>Sun Compass: Why the Clock Matters</h4>
            <p class="diagram-caption">
              The sun appears to move ~15° per hour across the sky. Without an internal clock to
