          <div class="summary-box">
            <h4>Classic Evidence: Clock-Shifted Bees &amp; Pigeons</h4>
            <p>
              Scientists proved the clock component by keeping animals in artificial light cycles
              shifted by 6 hours. When released, <strong>clock-shifted pigeons</strong> flew ~90°
              off course — exactly the error predicted if their internal clock was 6 hours wrong.
              This elegant experiment confirmed that the sun compass depends on a functioning
              circadian clock.
            </p>
          </div>


          <!-- ── Magnetic Navigation ── -->
          <h3>Magnetic Navigation</h3>

          <p>
            Earth's magnetic field provides a <strong>globally available</strong> directional cue
            that works day and night, in cloud, fog, and underwater. Many migratory species —
            birds, sea turtles, lobsters, salmon — can detect magnetic fields and use them for
            both compass direction and positional ("map") information.
          </p>

          <div class="key-concept">
            <h4>Two Types of Magnetic Information</h4>
            <div class="concept-pair">
              <div class="concept-card concept-card--mag-compass">
                <h5>Magnetic Compass (Inclination)</h5>
                <p>
                  Earth's field lines emerge vertically at the poles and run horizontally at the
                  equator. The <strong>inclination angle</strong> (dip angle) tells the animal
                  whether it is heading poleward or equatorward — functioning as a compass.
                </p>
                <p>
                  Birds appear to detect <strong>the axis of the field</strong> rather than its
                  polarity, distinguishing "poleward" from "equatorward" rather than magnetic
                  north from south.
                </p>
              </div>
              <div class="concept-card concept-card--mag-map">
                <h5>Magnetic Map (Intensity &amp; Inclination)</h5>
                <p>
                  Both <strong>total field intensity</strong> and <strong>inclination angle</strong>
                  vary geographically in a predictable way. By detecting both parameters, an animal
                  can estimate its <strong>latitude and longitude</strong> — a bicoordinate
                  magnetic map.
                </p>
                <p>
                  Sea turtles and lobsters have been shown to use this map sense to determine
                  their position relative to their goal.
                </p>
              </div>
            </div>
          </div>

          <!-- Magnetic field diagram -->
          <div class="nav-diagram">
            <h4>Earth's Magnetic Field Lines</h4>
            <p class="diagram-caption">
              Field lines emerge vertically at the poles and run parallel to the surface at the
