          </div>

          <div class="exam-tip">
            <h4>Exam Tip</h4>
            <p>
              Don't just say animals "sense the magnetic field." For Excellence, explain
              <strong>what information</strong> the field provides (inclination = compass direction;
              intensity + inclination = position) and <strong>how</strong> it is detected (magnetite
              crystals or cryptochrome proteins in the eye).
            </p>
          </div>

          <div class="key-concept">
            <h4>How Is the Magnetic Field Detected?</h4>
            <p>
              Two mechanisms have been proposed, and both may operate in different species:
            </p>
            <div class="concept-pair">
              <div class="concept-card concept-card--magnetite">
                <h5>Magnetite-Based Reception</h5>
                <p>
                  Tiny crystals of <strong>magnetite (Fe<sub>3</sub>O<sub>4</sub>)</strong> —
                  a naturally magnetic mineral — have been found in the beaks and nasal tissues of
                  birds, and in the brains of fish and sea turtles. These crystals physically rotate
                  in response to the magnetic field, stimulating nearby nerve cells.
                </p>
              </div>
              <div class="concept-card concept-card--cryptochrome">
                <h5>Radical Pair Mechanism (Cryptochrome)</h5>
                <p>
                  <strong>Cryptochrome proteins</strong> in the retina of birds are activated by
                  blue light and form radical pairs whose chemistry is influenced by the magnetic
                  field. This may allow birds to literally <strong>"see" the magnetic field</strong>
                  as a visual pattern overlaid on their normal vision.
                </p>
              </div>
            </div>
          </div>


          <!-- ── Star Navigation ── -->
          <h3>Star Navigation</h3>

          <p>
            Nocturnal migrants cannot use a sun compass. Instead, some species orient using
            <strong>star patterns</strong>. Unlike the sun, the stars' positions change slowly
            enough that no time compensation is needed within a single night — the pattern
            of constellations itself provides directional information.
          </p>

          <div class="key-concept">
            <h4>How Star Navigation Works</h4>
            <p>
              In the Northern Hemisphere, stars appear to rotate around <strong>Polaris</strong>
              (the pole star), which remains essentially stationary. Birds learn that the centre of
              celestial rotation = north. In the Southern Hemisphere, the
              <strong>Southern Cross</strong> and pointer stars serve a similar (though less
              precise) role.
            </p>
            <div class="concept-example">
              <span class="example-label">Classic experiment</span>
              <p>
                Stephen Emlen (1970s) raised <strong>indigo buntings</strong> in a planetarium.
                Birds raised under a normal star pattern oriented correctly. Birds raised under a
                <em>rotated</em> sky (where a different star was at the centre of rotation) treated
                that star as "north." This proved birds <strong>learn</strong> the star pattern
                during development — it is not innate.
              </p>
            </div>
          </div>

          <div class="exam-tip">
            <h4>Exam Tip</h4>
            <p>
              A common exam mistake is saying birds "follow Polaris." The key insight is that birds
              learn which point is the <strong>centre of celestial rotation</strong> — they don't
              innately know which star is the pole star.
            </p>
          </div>


          <!-- ── Olfactory Navigation ── -->
          <h3>Olfactory (Smell) Navigation</h3>

          <p>
            Some species use <strong>airborne or waterborne chemical cues</strong> for navigation
            over long distances — distinct from short-range chemotaxis.
          </p>

          <div class="key-concept">
            <h4>Olfactory Map Hypothesis</h4>
            <p>
              Homing pigeons may build an <strong>olfactory map</strong> by learning the
              characteristic smells carried by winds from different directions. When displaced,
              they sniff the local air, compare it to their learned odour map, and determine
              which direction is home. Pigeons with blocked nasal passages or severed olfactory
              nerves show severely impaired homing.
            </p>
          </div>

          <div class="summary-box">
            <h4>Salmon Homing — Olfactory Imprinting</h4>
            <p>
              Pacific salmon (<em>Oncorhynchus</em> spp.) famously return to their natal stream
              to spawn after years at sea. During a critical developmental window as juveniles,
              they <strong>imprint on the unique chemical signature</strong> of their home stream.
              Years later, they follow this chemical "address" upstream, using
              <strong>positive chemotaxis</strong> to trace the scent gradient to their birthplace.
              This is one of the most extraordinary examples of long-range chemically guided
              navigation in nature.
            </p>
          </div>


          <!-- ── Multi-Cue Navigation ── -->
          <h3>Multi-Cue Navigation: Putting It All Together</h3>

          <p>
            No single mechanism explains all of navigation. Real migrants use <strong>multiple
            cues redundantly</strong>, switching between them depending on conditions.
          </p>

          <div class="nav-diagram">
            <h4>Navigation Hierarchy</h4>
            <p class="diagram-caption">
              Long-distance migrants typically use different cues at different stages of the journey.
            </p>
