                </div>
                <h5>Arrival</h5>
                <p>Visual landmarks (piloting) + olfactory cues for final homing</p>
              </div>
            </div>
          </div>

          <div class="summary-box">
            <h4>Connection to Taxes</h4>
            <p>
              Navigation mechanisms are built on the same <strong>taxis</strong> responses you
              studied in Weeks 2–3. Sun compass navigation involves <strong>phototaxis</strong>
              (orientation to light). Magnetic navigation is <strong>magnetotaxis</strong>. Salmon
              homing is <strong>positive chemotaxis</strong>. The difference is <em>scale</em> —
              navigation operates over kilometres, but the underlying sensory mechanisms are the
              same directional responses to environmental stimuli.
            </p>
          </div>
        </section>


        <!-- ——————————————————————————————————————————————————————————————
             Navigation: NZ & Global Examples
             —————————————————————————————————————————————————————————————— -->
        <section id="nav-examples" class="content-section fade-in-up">
          <h2>Navigation: NZ &amp; Global Examples</h2>

          <p>
            These examples demonstrate how different species combine navigation mechanisms.
            NZ species are particularly interesting because of the vast oceanic distances involved.
          </p>

          <!-- ── NZ Examples ── -->
          <h3>New Zealand Species</h3>

          <div class="examples-grid">

            <!-- Bar-tailed godwit -->
            <div class="example-card example-card--nz example-card--featured">
              <div class="example-card__header">
                <h4>Bar-Tailed Godwit / Kuaka</h4>
                <span class="example-card__latin">Limosa lapponica baueri</span>
                <span class="response-badge response-badge--nav">Magnetic + sun compass</span>
              </div>
              <div class="example-card__body">
                <p>
                  Holds the record for the <strong>longest non-stop flight of any bird</strong> —
                  up to <strong>13,000 km</strong> from Alaska to NZ without landing, eating, or
                  drinking, taking 8–10 days of continuous flight over the Pacific Ocean.
                </p>
                <p>
                  With no landmarks over open ocean, godwits must rely on <strong>magnetic compass</strong>
                  and <strong>time-compensated sun compass</strong> navigation. They depart Alaska in
                  September and arrive at NZ estuaries (Miranda, Farewell Spit, Avon-Heathcote) in
                  October. Juveniles make their first journey <strong>without parental guidance</strong>,
                  suggesting an inherited magnetic direction programme.
                </p>
                <p class="example-card__detail">
                  In 2022, a satellite-tagged godwit (4BBRW) flew 13,560 km non-stop from Alaska to
                  near Invercargill in 11 days — setting a new world record. These birds lose up to
                  55% of their body mass during the flight, having converted most of their internal
                  organs to fuel before departure.
                </p>
              </div>
            </div>

            <!-- Sooty shearwater -->
            <div class="example-card example-card--nz">
              <div class="example-card__header">
                <h4>Sooty Shearwater / Tītī</h4>
                <span class="example-card__latin">Ardenna grisea</span>
                <span class="response-badge response-badge--nav">Multi-cue (64,000 km)</span>
              </div>
              <div class="example-card__body">
                <p>
                  Breeds on NZ offshore islands (Whenua Hou / Codfish Island, The Snares) then
                  undertakes a <strong>figure-8 migration across the entire Pacific</strong> —
                  approximately <strong>64,000 km per year</strong>, one of the longest migrations
                  of any animal.
                </p>
                <p class="example-card__detail">
                  GPS tracking shows they follow a consistent trans-Pacific route: NZ → Japan/North
                  Pacific → Alaska/Canada → California → back to NZ. They use prevailing wind
                  patterns (anemotaxis) combined with magnetic and celestial cues. Muttonbirding
                  (tītī harvesting) by Ngāi Tahu is a protected cultural practice.
                </p>
              </div>
            </div>

            <!-- Long-finned eel -->
            <div class="example-card example-card--nz">
              <div class="example-card__header">
                <h4>Longfin Eel / Tuna</h4>
                <span class="example-card__latin">Anguilla dieffenbachii</span>
                <span class="response-badge response-badge--nav">Magnetic + olfactory</span>
              </div>
              <div class="example-card__body">
                <p>
                  NZ's endemic longfin eel lives in freshwater for <strong>up to 80 years</strong>
                  before migrating to the deep Pacific (thought to be near Tonga) to spawn and die.
                  The exact spawning grounds have <strong>never been found</strong>.
                </p>
                <p class="example-card__detail">
                  Juvenile glass eels return to NZ and navigate upstream using olfactory cues and
                  positive rheotaxis (swimming against current). Their magnetic sense is thought to
                  guide them across open ocean. This species is classified as "At Risk — Declining"
                  due to habitat loss and barriers to migration (dams, weirs).
                </p>
              </div>
            </div>

            <!-- Humpback whale -->
            <div class="example-card example-card--nz">
              <div class="example-card__header">
                <h4>Humpback Whale</h4>
                <span class="example-card__latin">Megaptera novaeangliae</span>
                <span class="response-badge response-badge--nav">Magnetic + acoustic</span>
              </div>
              <div class="example-card__body">
                <p>
                  Migrates <strong>~5,000 km</strong> between Antarctic feeding grounds (krill) and
                  warm breeding waters around Tonga, Raoul Island, and NZ's Kermadec Islands.
                  Research shows humpbacks follow <strong>remarkably straight courses</strong>
                  across open ocean, deviating less than 1° — strongly suggesting magnetic compass use.
                </p>
                <p class="example-card__detail">
                  A 2011 study found humpback whale migration tracks correlated with Earth's
                  geomagnetic field lines rather than ocean currents, supporting magnetic navigation.
                  NZ's Cook Strait is an important transit corridor.
                </p>
              </div>
            </div>

          </div>


          <!-- ── Global Examples ── -->
          <h3>Famous Global Examples</h3>

          <div class="examples-grid">

            <!-- Monarch butterfly -->
            <div class="example-card example-card--global example-card--featured">
              <div class="example-card__header">
                <h4>Monarch Butterfly — Multi-Generational Migration</h4>
                <span class="example-card__latin">Danaus plexippus</span>
                <span class="response-badge response-badge--nav">Sun compass + magnetic</span>
              </div>
              <div class="example-card__body">
                <p>
                  North American monarchs migrate <strong>up to 4,000 km</strong> from Canada/USA
                  to overwintering sites in central Mexico. They use a <strong>time-compensated sun
                  compass</strong> located in their antennae — remarkably, the antennae contain
                  both the clock and the compass sensor.
                </p>
                <p>
                  The return journey north takes <strong>multiple generations</strong>. The autumn
                  migrants that fly south are great-great-grandchildren of the butterflies that left
                  Mexico the previous spring. The navigational programme must therefore be
                  <strong>entirely inherited</strong> — no learning from parents is possible.
                </p>
                <p class="example-card__detail">
                  Clock-shift experiments confirm the sun compass: monarchs kept in 6-hour shifted
                  light cycles flew ~90° off course, just like clock-shifted pigeons. A magnetic
                  compass serves as a backup on overcast days.
                </p>
              </div>
            </div>

            <!-- Loggerhead sea turtle -->
            <div class="example-card example-card--global">
              <div class="example-card__header">
                <h4>Loggerhead Sea Turtle</h4>
                <span class="example-card__latin">Caretta caretta</span>
                <span class="response-badge response-badge--nav">Magnetic map</span>
              </div>
              <div class="example-card__body">
                <p>
                  Hatchlings in Florida enter the Atlantic and use a <strong>bicoordinate magnetic
                  map</strong> to navigate the North Atlantic gyre — a circular current system.
                  Lohmann's lab showed that exposing hatchlings to magnetic fields matching
                  different Atlantic locations caused them to swim in the <strong>direction that
                  would keep them within the gyre</strong>.
                </p>
                <p class="example-card__detail">
                  Adults return to nest on the <strong>same beach</strong> where they hatched,
                  decades later. They likely use magnetic coordinates to locate the general area,
                  then olfactory cues for final homing — a multi-cue strategy.
                </p>
              </div>
            </div>

            <!-- Arctic tern -->
            <div class="example-card example-card--global">
              <div class="example-card__header">
                <h4>Arctic Tern</h4>
                <span class="example-card__latin">Sterna paradisaea</span>
                <span class="response-badge response-badge--nav">Multi-cue (71,000 km)</span>
              </div>
              <div class="example-card__body">
                <p>
                  Holds the record for the <strong>longest annual migration</strong> — approximately
                  <strong>71,000 km</strong> pole to pole, from Arctic breeding grounds to Antarctic
                  feeding waters and back. Over a 30-year lifespan, an Arctic tern may fly the
                  equivalent of <strong>three round trips to the Moon</strong>.
                </p>
                <p class="example-card__detail">
                  They experience more daylight than any other animal, breeding under the midnight
                  sun and feeding under Antarctic summer light. Their navigation likely combines
                  magnetic compass, sun compass, and wind patterns.
                </p>
              </div>
            </div>

            <!-- Spiny lobster -->
            <div class="example-card example-card--global">
              <div class="example-card__header">
                <h4>Spiny Lobster — Magnetic Map in an Invertebrate</h4>
                <span class="example-card__latin">Panulirus argus</span>
                <span class="response-badge response-badge--nav">Magnetic map</span>
              </div>
              <div class="example-card__body">
                <p>
                  Caribbean spiny lobsters can determine their <strong>position</strong> (not just
                  direction) from the magnetic field alone. When displaced to unfamiliar locations,
                  they orient directly homeward — even when denied access to visual, chemical,
                  and wave cues.
                </p>
                <p class="example-card__detail">
                  This was one of the first demonstrations of a <strong>true magnetic map sense</strong>
                  in an invertebrate, showing that magnetic navigation is not limited to vertebrates.
                </p>
              </div>
            </div>

          </div>
